entry.content:
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<style>
  #cb {
    position: relative;
    width: 200px;
    height: 200px;
    border: 1px solid black;
  }

  #anchor {
    anchor-name: --a;
    position: absolute;
    width: 40px;
    height: 30px;
    left: 75px;
    top: 75px;
    background: coral;
  }

  #target {
    position: absolute;
    background: seagreen;
    width: 50px;
    height: 50px;
  }

</style>
<div id=cb>
  <div id=anchor></div>
  <div id=target>X</div>
</div>
<script>
  target.offsetTop;
  target.style = `
    width:anchor-size(--a width, 50px);
    height:anchor-size(--a height, 50px);
  ';
</script>
<p>
  The green box should be the same size as the orange box.
</p>
```

Framework detection: This uses JS RegExp APIs, but it does so with an existing context instead of the ScriptRegexp context. A potential issue is that we don't know if the context's RegExp prototype has been changed in JS, which could result in running arbitrary code, however unlikely. This isn't the case for ScriptRegexp since we control that context. As an example, the following snippet causes the user code to run when doing version detection:


<!DOCTYPE html>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>Framework Detection RegExp</title>

<script>
window.next = {version:"1.2.3"};
RegExp.prototype.exec = function() {
  console.log('MUHAHAHAHA');
  return "5000";
}
</script>

<h1>Test</h1>
